result.execSummary:
The defendant Michael R. Hayes was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).
  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Consecutive to: Any other sentence Defendant may be serving.

miscConds.notes: Defendant to remain employed or seek employment as determined by the Supervising Agent.

Defendant to maintain timely, uninterrupted payments as ordered in Waushara Co Case No. 1992PA000004.  Orders subject to modification in the future by further order of the Court. All payments are to be paid through the Wisconsin Support Collections Trust Fund (WISCTF), not through the Department of Corrections.
Defendant is to maintain a current address with the Waushara Co Child Support Agency.   DNA sample to be provided if Defendant has not previously provided a sample.

Court finds Defendant is indigent and will waive all Court Costs as to both counts.  As to 2004CF000001 the Court also finds the Defendant is indigent and will waive any repayment of the outstanding $490.00 balance.

timeConds.notes:
No Good Time Credit.  Huber Privileges granted to the extent Defendant is able to exercise work release.
